  "description": "Gold standard annotation for JCPOA nuclear negotiations benchmark. Covers the Iran nuclear dispute including P5+1 negotiations, IAEA verification, sanctions architecture, and regional dynamics.",
  "source_text": "The Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) was signed on July 14, 2015, between Iran and the P5+1 (United States, United Kingdom, France, Russia, China, and Germany), with the European Union serving as coordinator. The agreement required Iran to limit its uranium enrichment to 3.67% purity, reduce its stockpile of enriched uranium by 98%, and cap its centrifuge count at approximately 6,104 IR-1 machines for a period of ten years. In return, the United States, European Union, and United Nations would lift nuclear-related economic sanctions against Iran.\n\nThe International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) was tasked with verifying Iranian compliance through enhanced inspections under the Additional Protocol. The IAEA confirmed in multiple quarterly reports between 2016 and 2018 that Iran was meeting its obligations under the deal.\n\nOn May 8, 2018, US President Donald Trump announced the withdrawal of the United States from the JCPOA, reinstating all previously waived sanctions under a policy of 'maximum pressure.' The European signatories — the United Kingdom, France, and Germany (the E3) — opposed the withdrawal and attempted to preserve the agreement through the creation of INSTEX, a special purpose vehicle for trade with Iran.\n\nFollowing the US withdrawal, Iran began systematically reducing its JCPOA commitments in July 2019, exceeding enrichment limits and expanding its centrifuge operations. The assassination of IRGC-Quds Force commander Qasem Soleimani by a US drone strike on January 3, 2020, further escalated tensions. Iran announced it would no longer observe any operational limits under the JCPOA.\n\nIsrael, led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, had long opposed the JCPOA, characterizing Iran's nuclear program as an existential threat. Saudi Arabia shared Israel's concerns about Iranian regional influence through proxies including Hezbollah in Lebanon.\n\nBy February 2023, the IAEA confirmed that Iran had enriched uranium to 83.7% purity at the Fordow facility, approaching weapons-grade material. Iran's breakout time — the time needed to produce enough fissile material for one nuclear weapon — had shrunk to approximately twelve days.\n\nIndirect negotiations in Vienna between 2021 and 2022, mediated by the EU, produced a near-final agreement text but collapsed over Iran's demand that the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps be removed from the US Foreign Terrorist Organization list. In September 2024, the E3 triggered the JCPOA snapback mechanism, reimposing all pre-2015 UN sanctions on Iran.",
